# AI Product Analytics Dashboard — Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
This is a portfolio project for AI Product Management roles.
It's a Streamlit dashboard that tracks analytics for an AI-powered SaaS product.
Built by a beginner using Cursor AI. Keep code simple, well-commented, and readable.

## Stack
- Frontend/App: Streamlit (Python)
- Database: SQLite (local, via utils/db.py)
- Charts: Plotly (via components/charts.py)
- Data: Seeded via data/seed_data.py (no real backend needed)

## Project Structure
- app.py → main entry point, navigation
- pages/ → one file per dashboard page
- components/ → reusable UI pieces (charts, KPI cards, sidebar)
- utils/ → db connection and helper functions
- data/ → schema + seed script

## Dashboard Pages
1. LLM Metrics — token usage, cost per query, latency, model comparison
2. Feature Adoption — which AI features users are using and how often
3. User Retention — DAU/WAU/MAU, cohort retention, churn signals
4. Funnel — user journey from signup → first AI use → power user

## Coding Rules
- Always add comments explaining WHAT and WHY, not just what the code does
- Use Plotly for all charts (not matplotlib)
- Use st.metric() for KPI cards
- Keep each page file under 150 lines — split into components if needed
- Use utils/db.py for ALL database access, never raw sqlite3 calls in pages
- Seed data should look realistic (not round numbers, include anomalies)
- Color scheme: use a consistent palette defined in utils/helpers.py

## AI PM Context
When generating insights or copy for the dashboard, think like a product manager:
- Surface actionable insights, not just numbers
- Add "so what" callouts (e.g., "Latency spiked 40% on Dec 3 — correlates with model upgrade")
- Use PM terminology: DAU, retention, activation, aha moment, north star metric
